description:
### Company or project name
ClickHouse
### Describe what's wrong
@serxa and I have been working on introducing max_remote_{read|write}_network_bandwidth_for_server settings across the cloud to reduce the occurrence of the network noisy neighbour issue. Despite a number of improvements to the throttler in 25.8, I noticed that an instance (feldspar-me-50) with these settings continues to take daily backups whose throughput goes above the limit. I was able to reproduce the issue on a test instance. Please see reproduction notes for more details.
**AI-generated notes regarding the relevant code and the root cause (reviewed by @andreev-io):**
_Root Cause_
The throttler's maximum sleep duration is capped by max_block_ns, derived from the socket's receive timeout: [base/poco/Net/src/SocketImpl.cpp:1096-1097](https://github.com/ClickHouse/ClickHouse/blob/master/base/poco/Net/src/SocketImpl.cpp#L1096-L1097)
```
if (_recvTimeout.totalMicroseconds() != 0)
_recvThrottler->throttle(amount, _recvTimeout.totalMicroseconds() * 1000 / 2);
```
With adaptive timeouts enabled (default s3_use_adaptive_timeouts = true), the receive timeout for S3 GET requests is overridden to 500ms: [src/IO/ConnectionTimeouts.cpp:110-118](https://github.com/ClickHouse/ClickHouse/blob/master/src/IO/ConnectionTimeouts.cpp#L110-L118)
```
static constexpr Poco::Timestamp::TimeDiff rest_bytes_ms[known_methods_count][2] =
{
/* GET */ {500, 500},
// ...
};
```
This results in max_block_ns = 250ms. When the throttler calculates that it needs to sleep longer than 250ms to pay off accumulated debt, the sleep is truncated: [src/Common/Throttler.cpp:85-94](https://github.com/ClickHouse/ClickHouse/blob/master/src/Common/Throttler.cpp#L85-L94)
```
double block_ns_double = -tokens_value / max_speed_value * NS;
// ...
sleepForNanoseconds(std::min<UInt64>(max_block_ns, block_ns));
```
With N concurrent threads all hitting this 250ms cap, the throttler can never catch up with the accumulated debt, and throughput exceeds the configured limit.
_Why query-level s3_use_adaptive_timeouts = 0 doesn't help_
The S3 client for disk storage is created at server startup, not query time: [src/Disks/DiskObjectStorage/ObjectStorages/ObjectStorageFactory.cpp:132-134](https://github.com/ClickHouse/ClickHouse/blob/master/src/Disks/DiskObjectStorage/ObjectStorages/ObjectStorageFactory.cpp#L132-L134)
```
auto settings = std::make_unique<S3Settings>();
settings->loadFromConfigForObjectStorage(config, config_prefix, context->getSettingsRef(), ...);
auto client = getClient(endpoint, *settings, context, /* for_disk_s3 */ true, name);
```
The settings loading checks query settings only as a fallback if the disk config doesn't specify the value, and only at disk initialization time: [src/IO/S3AuthSettings.cpp:103-114](https://github.com/ClickHouse/ClickHouse/blob/master/src/IO/S3AuthSettings.cpp#L103-L114)
```
for (auto & field : impl->allMutable())
{
auto path = fmt::format("{}.{}", config_prefix, field.getName());
bool updated = setValueFromConfig(config, path, field);  // First: disk config
if (!updated)
{
auto setting_name = "s3_" + field.getName();
if (settings.has(setting_name) && settings.isChanged(setting_name))
field.setValue(settings.get(setting_name));  // Fallback: context settings
}
}
```
Once created, the S3 client is reused for all queries. Query-level settings have no effect on disk storage reads.
_Suggested Fixes_
- Exempt throttler sleep from adaptive timeouts: Adaptive timeouts are meant to fail fast on unresponsive connections, not to limit intentional throttling delays. The throttler should use a separate mechanism not subject to receive timeout caps.
